Sure, here's a simple example of how you might write a C++ program to count the occurrences of a specific word in a text file.

First, you'll need to include the necessary libraries:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <fstream>
#include <string>
```

Next, you can define your main function:

```cpp
int main() {
    std::string word_to_count = "your_word_here";
    std::string word_from_file;
    int count = 0;
    std::ifstream file("your_file.txt");

    if (!file) {
        std::cout << "Unable to open file";
        return 1; // exit with error
    }

    while (file >> word_from_file) {
        if (word_from_file == word_to_count) {
            count++;
        }
    }

    file.close();
    std::cout << "The word \"" << word_to_count << "\" occurred " << count << " times in the file." << std::endl;

    return 0;
}
```

This program works by opening the specified file and continuously reading words from it until there are no more words left to read. Each word is compared to the target word, and if they match, the count is incremented. Once all words have been read, the total count is printed out.

Please replace "your_word_here" with the word you're looking for and "your_file.txt" with your file's name.

Remember that this program only works for exact matches, so "Word" and "word" would be treated as different words, and punctuation is also considered part of the word. If you want to improve this, you might want to consider converting all strings to lowercase and removing punctuation before comparison.

Please note that you should compile this program with a C++ compiler and run the resulting executable to test it.
